body:
## Example
```systemverilog
class Base;
  function new(int x);
  endfunction
endclass
class Derived extends Base;
  function new;
    int x = 1;
    super.new(x);
  endfunction
endclass
```
Above code snippet verilates but fails on ``C++`` compilation stage.

Error:
```
In file included from Vl__ALL.cpp:8:
Vl___024unit__03a__03aDerived__Vclpkg__DepSet_h3f0e46e6__0.cpp: In constructor ‘Vl___024unit__03a__03aDerived::Vl___024unit__03a__03aDerived(Vl__Syms*)’:
Vl___024unit__03a__03aDerived__Vclpkg__DepSet_h3f0e46e6__0.cpp:10:43: error: ‘x’ was not declared in this scope
   10 |     : Vl___024unit__03a__03aBase(vlSymsp, x) {
      |                                           ^
```

Command:
```bash
$VERILATOR --binary -O0 file.v
```
Important here is ``-O0``. However, this issue can be replicated without ``-O0`` with a bit more complex example.

## Cause
Verilator generates ``C++`` code presented below:
```C++
Vm___024unit__03a__03aDerived::Vm___024unit__03a__03aDerived(Vm__Syms* __restrict vlSymsp)
    : Vm___024unit__03a__03aBase(vlSymsp, x) {
    VL_DEBUG_IF(VL_DBG_MSGF("+          Vm___024unit__03a__03aDerived::new\n"); );
    // Init
    _ctor_var_reset(vlSymsp);
    // Body
    IData/*31:0*/ x;
    x = 0;
    x = 1U;
    ;
}
```

The problem is that `x` variable is referenced in the call of the base class constructor, but the declaration is in the body below.

## Environment:
### Verilator version
```bash
$VERILATOR --version
Verilator 5.039 devel rev UNKNOWN.REV
```
(built from this [commit](https://github.com/verilator/verilator/commit/98b8d43a4ae52dba9d42422e61c76c52be5d5c0d))

### **OS**
``Debian 12``
### **g++**
```bash
g++ --version
g++ (Debian 12.2.0-14+deb12u1) 12.2.0
Copyright (C) 2022 Free Software Foundation, Inc.
This is free software; see the source for copying conditions.  There is NO
warranty; not even for MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.
```

## Solutions
Here we want to propose two potential solutions to this issue - both changing the way objects in ``C++`` are constructed.

Solution will use the following code as an example (it contains more complex cases than the example above).
```systemverilog
class Base;
  function new(int x);
  endfunction
endclass
class Derived extends Base;
  int a;
  int b = 3;
  function new;
    int x = 1;
    super.new(x);
    $write("%d\n", x);
    b += 4;
    a = 7;
    $write("x: %d b: %d\n", x, y, b);
  endfunction
endclass
```

### Solution 1 - ``init`` method
First solution is to instantiate empty object first and then use ``init()`` method as a proper object setup.

Example ``C++`` code for example above:
```C++
#include <iostream>

struct VlSymsp {};

class Base {
public:
    Base(){}
    Base(VlSymsp vlSymsp, int o){ init(vlSymsp, o); }
    void init(VlSymsp vlSymsp, int o) { std::cout << "[DEBUG]: GOT: " << o << '\n'; }
    Base(const Base&) {std::cout << "[DEBUG]: COPY\n";}
    Base(Base&&) {std::cout << "[DEBUG]: MOVE\n";}
};

class Derived : Base {
    int a;
    int b = 3;
public:
    Derived(){ }
    Derived(VlSymsp vlSymsp) { init(vlSymsp); }
    void init(VlSymsp vlSymsp) {
        int x = 1;
        Base::init(vlSymsp, x);
        b += 4;
        a = 7;
        std::cout << "x: " << x << " b: " << b << '\n';
    }
};
```
It is simple, but I don't like the fact it instantiates empty objects and then fixes them.


### Solution 2 - static factory function
Using static factory function to allow calls before construction of base object and allow sharing variables between before and after super call.

Example ``C++`` code for above example:
```C++
#include <iostream>

class Base {
    struct SuperArgs {};
    Base(SuperArgs&&, int o) { std::cout << "[DEBUG]: GOT: " << o << '\n'; }
public:
    Base(const Base&) {std::cout << "[DEBUG]: COPY\n";}
    Base(Base&&) {std::cout << "[DEBUG]: MOVE\n";}
    static Base create(int o) {
        return Base(SuperArgs{}, o);
    }
};

class Derived : Base {
    int a;
    int b /* = 3*/;
    struct SuperArgs {
        int x;  // We have to add here every variable that is being declated before super
    };
    Derived(SuperArgs&& args): Base{Base::create(args.x)}, b(3) {
        std::cout << args.x << '\n';
        b += 4;
        a = 7;
        std::cout << "x: " << args.x << " b: " << b << '\n';
    }
public:
    static Derived create() {
        return Derived(SuperArgs{
            /*.x: */ 1,
        });
    }
};
```

It is much more complex and involves calling move constructor of the base class. However, it doesn't instantiate empty objects.

I believe that first one is much simpler and if there is no complex objects inside classes it can be used. However, if for some reason we do not want to create empty uninitialized objects then second solution satisfies us.


Which solution shall be implemented? Do you have any other ideas?
